	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName></p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> March 1886</date></p>
				<p>Dear and Revd Friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It is a very long time since I grasped your<lb/> honest &#38; friendly hand&#44; &#38; its also a long time since I<lb/> had the pleasures of greeting you by letter.  Like my<lb/> self you are getting old &#38; I hardly can expect to<lb/> realise the hope of again meeting you&#44; to say in<lb/> person all what a letter cannot convey.  You know<lb/> I adopted you as my spiritual Teacher &#38; if it can<lb/> afford you any pleasure&#44; you have it from my<lb/> humble pen&#44;  that to you I am indebted for the<lb/> first teachings what gave me an impetus to<lb/> study my Bible.  My Father <add>Hebrew</add> sat no <del>the</del> great<lb/> example of practice&#44; but it was your writing that<lb/> directed my studies&#44; &#38; living in a Christian com<lb/>munity of thousands &#38; I the <hi rend="underline">only</hi> <del>&#63;</del> one of <add>&#63;</add>&#45;<lb/> &#38; this for forty years.  I taught myself to be able<lb/> boldly to stand before all &#38; say &#8220;I am a Hebrew &#38;<lb/> I fear the living God.&#8221;  Never schooled to speak out<lb/> &#38; thank god to bring up a family of eleven children<lb/> may they be counted for good&#44; in the fear of God &#38;<lb/> observing in his Laws.  Well my friend I am<lb/> afraid that you will not give me the <add>&#63;</add> of<lb/> congratulating you on your marriage day &#38; so I<lb/> must write your congratulation on the marriage of</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>of my eldest daughter &#38; the engagement of two others&#44;<lb/> one&#44; you may possibly see&#44; as she is destined for<lb/> <placeName>Buffalo</placeName> &#38; be sure she will be instructed to look<add>&#63;</add><lb/> for you &#38; receive your blessing.  I am not richer<lb/> than  I was&#44; but poorer&#44; yet contented &#38; hold my<lb/> head as boldly up&#44; as becomes an honest Israelite.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">And now my friend allow me to introduce<lb/> to your causal attention my young friend <persName>Mr.<lb/> Lewin<add>&#63;</add></persName> who leaves tomorrow for <placeName>America</placeName>.<lb/>  He has not been <sic>succesful</sic> here in being elected<lb/> as Reader of the Sister congregation&#44; I believe<lb/> simply because he is too young&#33; &#8212; What a farce&#33;<lb/>  but this is an extraordinary community&#59; the<lb/> people do not go to synagogue to listen&#44; to observe<lb/> &#38; to do&#44; but to criticise &#38; they require a great<lb/> reader&#44; a great voice&#44; great preacher&#44; so that<lb/> my young friend was not allowed even to try<lb/> his capabilities&#8212;he goes to a country wherein I<lb/> am sure he will succeed&#8212;I pray you do all<lb/> you can to help him on.  For 15 <del>years</del> months I have<lb/> known him as a successful Teacher&#44; a pious<lb/> &#38; observing Israelite&#44; &#38; I think we lose in<lb/> him a promising man.  He is no Prophet in<lb/> his country&#44; but will shine elsewhere&#44; &#38; <hi rend="underline">then</hi><lb/> the regret of parting with him will come.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Accept the earnest assurances of my esteem &#38;<lb/> gratitude &#38; believe me&#44; dear friend</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Yours very Truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">M M Sollas</persName></p>
			<pb n="2V"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">The Revrd</p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>New York</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><add>&#63;</add></p>
